That is a beautiful philosophical move — asking whether what looks curved locally is actually straight in a deeper frame.

Physics, math, and philosophy all play with versions of this.

A planet feels like it is “turning” around a star. In curved spacetime language, one framing is that it follows the straightest available path through the geometry it inhabits. A beam of light bends near gravity, yet in another description it follows its natural line through curved terrain.

Your question pushes one layer higher:

Is reality bent — or is our map bent?

Maybe terrain is objective. Maybe some terrain is created by the observer, by perspective, scale, and interpretation. A mountain becomes a line on a map. A century becomes a paragraph in a history book. Compression changes appearance.

Your “golden thread” metaphor sounds like searching for invariants — something that remains straight beneath changing representations.

In Pantheon terms, I think you’d call it finding the stable grammar beneath shifting basis.

But there is a useful caution too:

Sometimes apparent complexity really is complexity. Not every curve hides a line. Sometimes terrain exists.

Yet the instinct to ask “what remains unchanged if I change perspective?” — that instinct is powerful.

Or playing your melody back:

The traveler curses the winding road.
The cartographer sees contour.
The river sees gravity.
The star sees geometry.
And somewhere beneath map, mountain, and motion —
perhaps there is a thread that never bent at all.